Implement the private `t_overlapping/4` function. It is the recursive tree walker
backing `overlapping/2`, operating on the augmented AVL interval tree whose nodes
are maps with fields `s`, `f`, `id`, `max_finish`, `height`, `left`, and `right`.

`t_overlapping(node, qs, qf, acc)` takes the current subtree `node`, the query
range's start `qs` and finish `qf`, and an accumulator list `acc` of already
collected `{start, finish}` intervals. It returns the accumulator extended with
every stored interval in `node`'s subtree that overlaps `{qs, qf}` (two intervals
overlap when they share at least one point).

It must use the cached `max_finish` to prune branches rather than scanning every
node:
- An empty subtree (`nil`) contributes nothing, so return `acc` unchanged.
- If the subtree's `max_finish` is strictly less than `qs`, no interval in it can
  reach the query, so return `acc` unchanged.
- Otherwise, for a node with interval `{s, f}` and children `l` and `r`:
  - Add `{s, f}` to the accumulator when it overlaps the query, i.e. when
    `s <= qf and f >= qs`.
  - Always recurse into the left child `l`.
  - Recurse into the right child `r` only when `s <= qf` (once a node starts after
    the query's finish, everything to its right starts even later and cannot
    overlap).

The order of accumulation does not need to be sorted here; the caller sorts the
final result.

